<h2>Key Takeaways</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Volar is currently incompatible with TypeScript 7.</strong> The monkey-patching approach cannot work with a Go binary. This is a known, tracked issue awaiting upstream resolution.</li>
  <li><strong>The Corsa API is IPC-based.</strong> TypeScript 7 exposes a curated API via STDIO pipes, using <code>libsyncrpc</code> (a Rust-based NAPI module) for synchronous calls from Node.js. This is intentionally language-agnostic.</li>
  <li><strong>Volar plugins cannot be written in Go today.</strong> Volar is a purely Node.js/TypeScript framework with no out-of-process plugin boundary. Native code would need to be wrapped via WASM or FFI, or communicate via IPC with a Volar plugin acting as a bridge.</li>
  <li><strong>The Oso pattern (Rust &rarr; WASM in a TS host) is the closest precedent</strong> for native code integration within a VS Code extension. TypeScript 7's own IPC architecture is the closest precedent for subprocess-based integration.</li>
  <li><strong>Volar's main bottleneck is the TypeScript language service itself.</strong> TypeScript 7's 7&ndash;10x speedup would directly benefit Volar users &mdash; once integration is possible.</li>
  <li><strong>IPC is the recommended pattern</strong> for connecting a Go-based analysis engine to a Volar plugin. It follows TypeScript 7's own architecture, avoids WASM binary size issues, and provides process isolation.</li>
</ol>


